  <h2>Making continuous colour palettes with RColorBrewer</h2>
<p>The <code>RColorBrewer</code> package makes choosing colours for your graphs easy.
If you follow the link on the help page for the handy <code>brewer.pal</code> function,
 you can get to a web app that lets you choose the type of palette (linear, diverging, qualitative),
 the number of colours and other options, like palettes that will be visable to people who are red-green colour
 blind (about 4% of the population).<br />This all extremely useful, but <code>RColorBrewer</code>
 palettes are generally limited to a maximum of 10 different colours. What if you want to have a continuous scale?
  Here I run through how to make a colour ramp from a Brewer palette.<br />Note though, that
   the designers of <code>RColorBrewer</code> limited the number of colours as a deliberate choice.
   The colour palettes are mainly designed for maps, and in general, people can't keep more than about 7
   categories in their head at any one time. Hence, before you create your figure, think about how you want to represent on your figure. For instance, say you are plotting elevation. Choosing a few colours will emphasis zones in elevation, for instance, maybe you want to represent different vegetation zones that change with altitude. Whereas, a continuous palette will obviously represent the data as more of a gradient.</p>
<div id="colour-brewer-categorical-colours" class="section level3">
<h3>Colour Brewer categorical colours</h3>
<pre class="r"><code>library(RColorBrewer)
bluecols &lt;- brewer.pal(9, 'Blues')</code></pre>
<p>Which just makes a pie with nine different shades of blue. ### A colour ramp We can use the <code>colorRampPalette()</code> function to create a new function, here <code>newcol()</code>. <code>newcol()</code> takes a single integer as an argument, which outputs the colour ramp using our blue palette.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>newcol &lt;- colorRampPalette(bluecols)
ncols &lt;- 100
bluecols2 &lt;- newcol(ncols)#apply the function to get 100 colours</code></pre>
<p>And that is it. We now have the <code>RColorBrewer</code> palette with 100 different shades of blue.</p>
